Although the CRM estimates show the proportion of merchantable biomass to be the same for all the softwood species of a given diameter, estimates from regional equations indicate that merchantable biomass differs not only by species but also by subregion (fig. 2). For Douglas-fir, the proportion of merchantable biomass to total aboveground biomass in east-side Oregon is lower than the proportion in west-side Oregon because the tree forms and stem taper in these two subregions are quite different.

